trans-unit.source: Identifies the linear combination of feature variables that can best group data into separate classes
trans-unit.target: Identifies the linear combination of feature variables that can best group data into separate classes

trans-unit.source: You can use the <ui>Fisher Linear Discriminant Analysis</ui> module to create a set of scores that identifies the combination of features that best separate two or more classes.
trans-unit.target: You can use the <ui>Fisher Linear Discriminant Analysis</ui> module to create a set of scores that identifies the combination of features that best separate two or more classes.

trans-unit.source: This method is often used for dimensionality reduction, because it projects a set of features onto a smaller feature space while preserving the information that discriminates between classes.
trans-unit.target: This method is often used for dimensionality reduction, because it projects a set of features onto a smaller feature space while preserving the information that discriminates between classes.

trans-unit.source: This not only reduces computational costs for a given classification task, but can help prevent overfitting.
trans-unit.target: This not only reduces computational costs for a given classification task, but can help prevent overfitting.

trans-unit.source: Note that Linear Discriminant Analysis is sometimes abbreviated to LDA, but this is easily confused with <newTerm>Latent Dirichlet Allocation</newTerm>.

trans-unit.source: How to Use Linear Discriminant Analysis
trans-unit.target: How to Use Linear Discriminant Analysis

trans-unit.source: You provide a set of possible feature columns as inputs, and the algorithm determines the optimal combination of the input columns that linearly separates each group of data while minimizing the distances within each group.
trans-unit.target: You provide a set of possible feature columns as inputs, and the algorithm determines the optimal combination of the input columns that linearly separates each group of data while minimizing the distances within each group.

trans-unit.source: To use linear discriminant analysis, your data must be complete (no missing values).
trans-unit.target: To use linear discriminant analysis, your data must be complete (no missing values).

trans-unit.source: It is also useful to have fewer predictors than there are samples
trans-unit.target: It is also useful to have fewer predictors than there are samples

trans-unit.source: Because the values are expected to have a normal distribution, you should review the data for outliers.
trans-unit.target: Because the values are expected to have a normal distribution, you should review the data for outliers.

trans-unit.source: After connecting your dataset, select a set of numeric feature columns as inputs.
trans-unit.target: After connecting your dataset, select a set of numeric feature columns as inputs.

trans-unit.source: The combination of eigenvectors and their values provides information about the shape of the linear transformation.
trans-unit.target: The combination of eigenvectors and their values provides information about the shape of the linear transformation.

trans-unit.source: In general, bigger scores (farther from zero) are better predictors.
trans-unit.target: In general, bigger scores (farther from zero) are better predictors.

trans-unit.source: When deciding which combination of variables to keep for the optimal (and smaller) dimensional subspace, you can eliminates the eigenvectors with the lowest values, because they contain the least information about the distribution of the data.
trans-unit.target: When deciding which combination of variables to keep for the optimal (and smaller) dimensional subspace, you can eliminates the eigenvectors with the lowest values, because they contain the least information about the distribution of the data.

trans-unit.source: In this example, the values in the eigenvectors all have a similar magnitude, which indicates that the data is projected onto a fairly good feature space.
trans-unit.target: In this example, the values in the eigenvectors all have a similar magnitude, which indicates that the data is projected onto a fairly good feature space.

trans-unit.source: However, if some of the eigenvalues were much larger than others, you would want to keep only those eigenvectors with the highest values, since they contain more information about the data distribution.
trans-unit.target: However, if some of the eigenvalues were much larger than others, you would want to keep only those eigenvectors with the highest values, since they contain more information about the data distribution.

trans-unit.source: That is, values that are closer to 0 are less informative and should be dropped when selecting a new set of features.
trans-unit.target: That is, values that are closer to 0 are less informative and should be dropped when selecting a new set of features.
